GO STATS

Since results were not significant, we wanted to check if this is still the case when trying out different libraries rather than clusterProfiler.

Tutorial

## Define universe and test sample set
# geneUniverse <- rownames(count.matrix)

geneUniverse <- bitr(rownames(count.matrix), 
     fromType="ENSEMBL", toType="ENTREZID", 
     OrgDb="org.Hs.eg.db")
## 'select()' returned 1:many mapping between keys and columns
## Warning in bitr(rownames(count.matrix), fromType = "ENSEMBL", toType =
## "ENTREZID", : 39.39% of input gene IDs are fail to map...
geneSample <-bitr(sig_005$ensembl_gene_id, 
     fromType="ENSEMBL", toType="ENTREZID", 
     OrgDb="org.Hs.eg.db")
## 'select()' returned 1:1 mapping between keys and columns
## Warning in bitr(sig_005$ensembl_gene_id, fromType = "ENSEMBL", toType =
## "ENTREZID", : 34% of input gene IDs are fail to map...
# geneUniverse <- keys(org.Hs.eg.db, keytype = "ENSEMBL")
# geneSample <- sig_005$ensembl_gene_id


## Generate params object

params <- new("GOHyperGParams", 
              geneIds = geneSample,
                universeGeneIds = geneUniverse,
                annotation="org.Hs.eg", ontology = "BP", pvalueCutoff = 0.05,
                conditional = FALSE, testDirection = "over")
## Warning in makeValidParams(.Object): converting geneIds from list to atomic
## vector via unlist
## Warning in makeValidParams(.Object): converting univ from list to atomic vector
## via unlist
## Warning in makeValidParams(.Object): removing duplicate IDs in universeGeneIds
## Run enrichment test - Hypergeometric test  
hgOver <- hyperGTest(params)
df<-summary(hgOver)
  
df$Adj.Pvalue <- p.adjust(df$Pvalue, 'bonferroni')

## Viewing of results
# summary(hgOver)

## 'select()' returned 1:1 mapping between keys and columns

react_ora <- compareCluster(
  geneClusters = gcUnique,# our significant genes
  fun = "enrichPathway", # ORA function to apply to each cluster
  organism = "human",
  pvalueCutoff = 1, # p-value filter: off
  qvalueCutoff = 1, # q-value filter: off
  pAdjustMethod = "BH", # p-values are adjusted within clusters
  universe = universe, # all genes
  minGSSize = 15,
  maxGSSize = 500
)

ggsave(plot=rnadot,
       filename = paste0(dir, "ANALYSIS/GoTermEnrichment/Plots/rnadot.png"),
       height = 5, width=9,dpi=320)

We get multiple significant results for collagen pathways and the gene TNRF1 is mentioned multipletimes. There is some literature on TNRF1 and endometriosis though: TNFR1 The paper mentions an downregulation of TNRF1 that can be associated with early stages of endometriosis. TNRF1 was not one of our DEGs. The gene from our data involved in that pathway is RNF31, which is indeed down in our dataset but we can find no literature further linking it to endometriosis.

Collagen was another result we could indeed find literature on. The gene in question is COL1A1. The authors found overexpression of COL1A1 in perilesional tissues (tissue around endometriosis lesions), but unfortunatly in our results COL1A1 is downregulated in patients from the diseased group compared to the control group. This might be for 2 reasons: 1) The paper mentions that COL1A1 might be upregulated in later stages of endometriosis due to its connection to scar tissue and fibrosis. That could possibly link to the downregulation found in TNFR1.

  1. The tissue mentioned is perilesional tissue. Unfortunately we have no further information from our data how much tissue around the lesions was collected.

No further litereature coud be found.

For our DMRs we couldn’t find some significant results using DOSE (p.adjust). The results are for glomerulosclerosis not directly for endometriosis. Glomerulosclerosis is a chronic kidney disease that leads to scarring of the We could find a paper linking endometriosis to chronic kidney disease CKD that mentions glomerulosclerosis. The Genes involved here from our Dataset are HR and IGFBP3. For HR we could find no further Literature linking it to endometriosis. For IGFBP3 we could find a paper linking it’s upregualtion to the pathophysiology of endometriosis and its possible involvement in the ectopic growth of endometriotic lesions. We could not find any information on its methylation status however.
